<font color="#FF0000">GUILT &amp; PATRIOTISM</font><br>
<tt>Wed Apr 23  2:24:05 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Have you ever noticed how clear this game is?  In the human psyche it is called rationalization.  How many people in life have to commit themselves to die for something...say one's country.  Those that stand up and take the 'call' are called men or women. Those that don't [who weasel out with some excuse, some reason or another] search the rest of their lives justifying their failure of responsibility to their fellow man.  Hey, friends, there aren’t many of us in a society.  You meet those other guys every day in our, or any society.  Those who serve should not enter into arguments with these folks that did not, for they are the unfortunate ones who try for a lifetime to rationalize out of that ultimate responsible sacrifice they failed to make.  And because there are so many, many more of them than us, they try, and try to build an environment to place the stigma and stress on the us, the guys and gals I would walk arm and arm with, anytime, anywhere; they are my fellow Americans.  We used to have a saying in training, “non-illigitamus carborundum”, in Latin means, don’t let the bastards grind you down.  Among men and women, you are the honored ones.  History shows that.  They, the excuse makers, carry this pain forever; it can never be erased except by trying to justify their particular individual excuses.  Take notice, there is a segment of our society designed to reduce the pain of guilt and the resultant behavior; we call them psychiatrists.  It is [not] fun for me to observe the very person educated and trained to reduce the psychological pain in another, attempt to justify and reduce his own pain.  I was 4-F, I got a deferment, I was in school, I wet my bed, it was an unjust war[only because we decided not to annihilate a nation?], I got married, I had two kids, I had a defense job, I joined the reserves, my senator got me into ROTC and I didn’t show up because I had to go to England as a Rhodes Scholar, and protest the war.  Oh brothers, give me a break.  If I had done that I would have had to carry the guilt for the rest of my life.  And, I would be disfunctional for it. Remember, guilt kills the inner self.  It east out your guts.  Those of you who served are the ones without guilt.  Those who did not serve spend the rest of their days rationalizing and building their defense mechanisms to justify this failure to perform.  Here is the real test, guys.  The next time you meet someone and the subject of Nam comes up and it is determined that you served and he did not, take notice of the silence.  That silence is their search to reduce the stress of their guilt; it is not that you did serve; you should be proud, but don't rub it in.  In closing, do not ever fall for the false guilt environment created after the Vietnam War by the political/media moguls that we were the bad guys.  You know right from wrong; it does not take a newspaper to establish the dominant social values of America for you.  And you are an American my friend.  Wake up friends.  Feel sorry not for yourselves.  Feel sorry for them.
<p><code>-- srg4444@primenet.com  (Stewart Gable) </code><p>


